                     </persName>
                     
                  , in his dwelling-house
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183209060130"></xptr>MR. PHILLIPS conducted the prosecution.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-306-person2529">
                  WILLIAM 
                  EDWARDS
               <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2529" type="surname" value="EDWARDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2529" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2529" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am foreman to Dickenson Sowerby, <rs id="t18320906-306-viclabel1729" type="occupation">pawnbroker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-306-victim2528 t18320906-306-viclabel1729"></join>, <placeName id="t18320906-306-crimeloc1730">Brick-lane, in the parish of St. Matthew, Bethnal-green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-306-crimeloc1730" type="placeName" value="Brick-lane, in the parish of St. Matthew, Bethnal-green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-306-crimeloc1730" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-306-off1727 t18320906-306-crimeloc1730"></join>. On the 29th of February, about seven o'clock in the evening, I was at tea in the parlour; our lad came in, and said a man wanted to look at a weddingring; I went and saw the prisoner, who said he wanted a wedding-ring to fit his little finger - I got some from the parlour, and showed him some in a paper; there were about forty - I took one out, and put the paper of rings by my arm; I said, "That is about the size you want;" it rolled along the counter, and I went to prevent its going off - he immediately snatched up the paper containing the rest from under my arm, and ran out instantly; I pursued, and caught him in the middle of the road, as he stumbled; we had a tussle two or three times - he was up and down; he screwed part of his coat up, and left part of it in my hand - two of his companions came up and knocked me down - he escaped; on the 17th of July I went with the officer to Kingsland-road, and saw the prisoner walking a match - I am quite certain he is the man; I had seen him about a week previous to the robbery, at the Crown and Shuttle, Shoreditch; the officer took him, and said, "I have caught you at last, Jemmy;" and took him to the station; I identified him immediately - I went to Worship-street with him in a coach, and a person who was with him said, "When this is all over, we will walk this match again;" he said, "I shan't walk it again, I suppose this will send me across the herring-pond."</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CLARKSON. Q. When had you seen him before? A. On the 29th of February; I did not seen him again till he was apprehended - I do not know that it was publicly announced, that he was going to walk a wager, but a man came to my shop, and said Danks was going to walk a wager; I knew his name, as when I saw him at the Crown and Shuttle, the week before, he came to my shop and bought a belt, he was talking about it being a good thing to walk with, and somebody said he was Jem Danks, the walking man; and he said,"I'll run you for 100l."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-306-person2530">
                  GEORGE 
                  LEE
               <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2530" type="surname" value="LEE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2530" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2530" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in the shop when the prisoner came in and run out with the rings; I am certain he is the man - I was standing by, writing a ticket at the time.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-306-person2531">
                  FRANCIS 
                  FARQUES
               <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2531" type="surname" value="FARQUES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2531" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-person2531" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a dyer, and live in Phoenix-street, Spitalfields. I had seen the prisoner two or three times before the 29th of February; I heard a noise at our gate that day, went out, and heard a cry of Stop thief! I opened the gate, saw the prisoner running, and pursued him; Edwards and several more were running after him - I saw a piece out of the shoulder of his coat; I caught him myself, but was knocked down by two or three, and he escaped - I am quite sure he is the man.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I have been placed here a second time on a capital charge; the first was on the 6th of April, when I was charged with robbing Mr. Wood, and had his Majesty's free pardon - he is brother-in-law to Sowerby, and he must know me; after receiving my pardon, I went into the employ of Mr. Bailey; and after this I was told if I walked for a wager, I should be taken into custody for robbing Sowerby, but knowing nothing of it, I went to walk the match - I knew Edwards, and saw him at his door on the 6th of July, and bid him good night; he said good night in reply - Lee said at Worship-street, that he did not believe I was the man.</p>
               <p>MR. EDWARDS. These rings were worth 10l.; they were not all stolen.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320906-306-verdict1731" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-verdict1731" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 19. - <rs id="t18320906-306-punish1732" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18320906-306-punish1732" type="punishmentCategory" value="transport"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-306-defend2526 t18320906-306-punish1732"></join>
               Transported for Life
            </rs>.</p>
